{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic, you will learn how to form and use the <strong>comparative</strong> and <strong>superlative</strong> forms of adjectives and adverbs correctly.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Base form",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Description without comparison:",
            "example": "This road is narrow."
        },
        {
            "label": "Comparative",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Comparing two things with <em>than</em>:",
            "example": "This road is narrower than that one."
        },
        {
            "label": "Superlative",
            "color": "rose",
            "text": "Picking out one item from a group with <em>the</em>:",
            "example": "This is the narrowest street in town."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Short words (1-2 syllables)",
    "intro": "For short adjectives, we add <code class=\"font-mono text-xs\">-er</code> / <code class=\"font-mono text-xs\">-est</code>:",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "General rule",
            "title": "-er / -est",
            "subtitle": "fast → faster → the fastest"
        },
        {
            "label": "Words ending in -y",
            "title": "-ier / -iest",
            "subtitle": "happy → happier → the happiest"
        },
        {
            "label": "Doubling the consonant",
            "title": "big → bigger",
            "subtitle": "When the pattern is consonant + vowel + consonant"
        },
        {
            "label": "Words ending in -e",
            "title": "-r / -st",
            "subtitle": "large → larger → the largest"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. Long words and adverbs",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "More / Most",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Adjectives with 3+ syllables and most adverbs use <strong>more / most</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "interesting → more interesting → the most interesting",
                    "ua": "interesting"
                },
                {
                    "en": "quickly → more quickly → the most quickly",
                    "ua": "quickly"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Less / Least",
            "color": "rose",
            "description": "For the opposite meaning, we use <strong>less / least</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "dangerous → less dangerous → the least dangerous",
                    "ua": "dangerous"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Two-syllable words",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "Some two-syllable adjectives allow both forms, especially those ending in <strong>-y</strong>, <strong>-ow</strong>, or <strong>-er</strong>:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "shallow → shallower / more shallow",
                    "ua": "shallow"
                },
                {
                    "en": "clever → cleverer / more clever",
                    "ua": "clever"
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Irregular forms",
    "intro": "Some adjectives and adverbs have special comparative and superlative forms:",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "good / well",
            "ua": "good / well",
            "note": "better → the best"
        },
        {
            "en": "bad / badly",
            "ua": "bad / badly",
            "note": "worse → the worst"
        },
        {
            "en": "far",
            "ua": "far",
            "note": "farther/further → the farthest/furthest"
        },
        {
            "en": "little (amount)",
            "ua": "little (amount)",
            "note": "less → the least"
        },
        {
            "en": "many / much",
            "ua": "many / much",
            "note": "more → the most"
        }
    ],
    "warning": "💡 <em>Further</em> is more common for the meaning “additional” or “later in time”, while <em>farther</em> usually refers to physical distance."
}

{
    "title": "4. Intensifying and softening comparison",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Intensifying comparatives",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Use <strong>much / way / a lot / far</strong> before a comparative:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "This is much better than before.",
                    "ua": "This is much better than before."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He runs way faster than me.",
                    "ua": "He runs way faster than me."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Intensifying superlatives",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "Use <strong>by far / easily</strong> before a superlative:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is by far the best student.",
                    "ua": "She is by far the best student."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Downtoners",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "Use <strong>slightly / a bit / a little</strong> for a small difference:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "This is slightly cheaper.",
                    "ua": "This is slightly cheaper."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Comparison structures",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "As ... as",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "For equality, use <strong>as + adjective/adverb + as</strong>:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She is as tall as her brother.",
                    "ua": "She is as tall as her brother."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He runs as fast as me.",
                    "ua": "He runs as fast as me."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Not as/so ... as",
            "color": "rose",
            "description": "For inequality, use <strong>not as/so + adjective + as</strong>:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "This book is not as interesting as that one.",
                    "ua": "This book is not as interesting as that one."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "The + superlative + in/of",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "To single out one item from a group:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He is the tallest in the class.",
                    "ua": "He is the tallest in the class."
                },
                {
                    "en": "This is the most useful of all.",
                    "ua": "This is the most useful of all."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "6. Typical mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Double comparison markers.",
            "wrong": "more better / the most fastest",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">better / the fastest</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Forgetting <strong>the</strong> before a superlative.",
            "wrong": "He is tallest in the class.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">He is the tallest in the class.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Using the wrong form after <strong>than</strong>.",
            "wrong": "My car is more reliable than your.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">My car is more reliable than yours.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "Other pages in the Adjectives category",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Degrees of Comparison",
            "url": "/theory/adjectives/theory-degrees-of-comparison"
        }
    ]
}
